SPACEX_REFERENCES: List[str] = [
    # Original 15
    "Falcon 9 is a two-stage orbital rocket designed by SpaceX for reliable and safe transport of people and payloads to Earth orbit and beyond. It is the first orbital class rocket capable of reflight — its first stage booster is recovered and reused, dramatically reducing launch costs. Falcon 9 has become the most frequently launched American rocket and achieved over 200 successful launches.",
    "Starship is SpaceX's fully reusable super heavy-lift launch system consisting of the Super Heavy booster and the Starship upper stage. It is designed to carry humans and cargo to the Moon, Mars, and beyond. NASA selected Starship as the Human Landing System for the Artemis program to return astronauts to the Moon. Starship is intended to be the most powerful rocket ever built.",
    "SpaceX Dragon is a reusable spacecraft developed to service the ISS under NASA's Commercial Resupply Services contract. Dragon became the first commercial spacecraft to deliver cargo to the ISS in 2012. The Crew Dragon variant (Dragon 2) became the first commercial spacecraft to carry NASA astronauts to the ISS, beginning with the Demo-2 mission in 2020.",
    "Starlink is SpaceX's satellite internet constellation providing broadband internet coverage globally. It consists of thousands of low Earth orbit satellites. Starlink generates significant recurring revenue for SpaceX, helping fund the development of Starship and other programs. Starlink has been deployed in conflict zones including Ukraine and serves customers in over 60 countries.",
    "SpaceX was founded in 2002 by Elon Musk with the goal of reducing space transportation costs and enabling the colonization of Mars. Musk was motivated partly by NASA's lack of plans for Mars exploration and by a desire to make humanity a multi-planetary species. He invested approximately $100 million of his own money from the PayPal acquisition into SpaceX's founding.",
    "The first three Falcon 1 launches (2006, 2007, 2008) all failed, nearly bankrupting SpaceX. The fourth Falcon 1 launch in September 2008 became the first privately developed liquid-fueled rocket to reach orbit. This success led directly to NASA awarding SpaceX a $1.6 billion Commercial Resupply Services contract, saving the company from bankruptcy.",
    "After stage separation, the Falcon 9 first stage booster performs a series of engine burns to return to the launch site or land on an autonomous drone ship at sea. Grid fins control descent attitude and landing legs deploy for touchdown. Boosters have been reflown over 10 times. This reusability is the primary driver of SpaceX's cost advantage, reducing launch prices significantly compared to expendable rockets.",
    "NASA selected SpaceX's Starship as the Human Landing System for the Artemis program to return astronauts to the lunar surface for the first time since Apollo 17. The contract is worth approximately $2.9 billion. SpaceX is responsible for developing and operating the lunar Starship variant, which will transport astronauts from lunar orbit to the surface and back.",
    "The Raptor is a full-flow staged combustion engine burning liquid methane and liquid oxygen, developed by SpaceX for Starship and Super Heavy. It is the first full-flow staged combustion engine to fly, achieving the highest chamber pressure of any production rocket engine. The Merlin engine, used on Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy, burns RP-1 (rocket grade kerosene) and liquid oxygen and uses an open-cycle gas generator design.",
    "Falcon Heavy is a heavy-lift launch vehicle consisting of three Falcon 9 cores strapped together, making it the most powerful operational rocket at its debut in 2018. Its first test flight carried Elon Musk's personal Tesla Roadster as a dummy payload into heliocentric orbit. Falcon Heavy has been used for US Air Force national security payloads and commercial geostationary satellites.",
    "Starlink operates in low Earth orbit at approximately 550km altitude, providing latency of 20-40ms compared to 600ms+ for traditional geostationary satellite internet. This low latency makes Starlink suitable for video calls and gaming unlike prior satellite internet. Starlink competes with ViaSat and HughesNet in rural broadband markets and has expanded to aviation and maritime applications.",
    "SpaceX faced significant regulatory hurdles from the FAA for Starship test flights from Boca Chica, Texas. Environmental groups challenged the FAA's environmental review process. The first integrated flight test in April 2023 was delayed due to regulatory approvals and the vehicle exploded during flight. SpaceX has also been in dispute with local communities and environmental advocates over impacts at Boca Chica.",
    "Crew Dragon (Dragon 2) is SpaceX's crewed spacecraft developed under NASA's Commercial Crew Program. Following the retirement of the Space Shuttle in 2011, the US paid Russia approximately $80 million per seat on Soyuz for ISS access. Crew Dragon's first crewed flight in May 2020 (Demo-2) restored US human launch capability. Crew Dragon regularly rotates NASA and international astronaut crews to the ISS.",
    "SpaceX's stated long-term goal is to make humanity multiplanetary by establishing a self-sustaining city on Mars. The company envisions sending thousands of Starship vehicles to Mars to build a colony of one million people within 50 years. The choice of methane as Starship's propellant is deliberate — methane can be synthesized on Mars using the Sabatier reaction from atmospheric CO2 and water ice, enabling in-situ propellant production for return flights.",
    "SpaceX generates revenue from three primary sources: launch services (commercial satellite launches, NASA contracts, US military national security launches via Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy), Starlink subscriptions (consumer, aviation, maritime, and government plans), and NASA contracts including Commercial Resupply Services and Commercial Crew. Starlink has grown rapidly and is reported to be the largest revenue contributor, helping cross-subsidize Starship development.",
    # New 35 references
    "SpaceX was founded in 2002 by Elon Musk, who serves as founder, chairman, CEO, and CTO. The company started with approximately 30 employees and has grown to over 13,000 by September 2023. Gwynne Shotwell serves as President and COO. The company's board includes Kimbal Musk, Luke Nosek, Steve Jurvetson, Antonio Gracias, and Donald Harrison.",
    "Falcon 1 was SpaceX's first orbital rocket. The first three launches in 2006, 2007, and 2008 all failed, nearly bankrupting SpaceX. The fourth launch in September 2008 became the first privately developed liquid-fueled rocket to reach orbit. All Falcon 1 launches took place at the Ronald Reagan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site on Omelek Island in the Marshall Islands.",
    "Dragon XL is a spacecraft contracted by NASA in March 2020 to send supplies to the Lunar Gateway space station. Dragon XL will be launched on a Falcon Heavy rocket. It extends SpaceX's cargo delivery capabilities beyond the ISS to lunar orbit.",
    "NASA's COTS (Commercial Orbital Transportation Services) program awarded SpaceX a Phase 1 contract in 2006 to demonstrate cargo delivery to the ISS. NASA paid SpaceX $396 million to develop the cargo Dragon, while SpaceX developed Falcon 9 with its own resources. These Space Act Agreements saved NASA millions, making rocket development 4-10 times less expensive than traditional NASA contracting.",
    "Commercial Resupply Services (CRS) contracts were awarded by NASA from 2008 to 2016. The first CRS contract awarded SpaceX $1.6 billion for 12 cargo missions. NASA extended the Phase 1 contracts to 20 total missions. In Phase 2, SpaceX was awarded up to nine additional flights using the upgraded Dragon 2 spacecraft. The final Dragon 1 mission departed the ISS in April 2020.",
    "SpaceX's McGregor, Texas facility is a rocket engine test facility where every engine and thruster must pass final testing before flight missions. As of 2024, over 7,000 tests had been conducted since it opened, with seven engine test fires on a typical day across more than a dozen test stands. The facility was originally the Bluebonnet Ordnance Plant from World War II. COO Gwynne Shotwell maintains her primary office there.",
    "Starlink's satellite manufacturing campus occupies over 314,000 square feet in Redmond, Washington, east of Seattle. The first building opened in early 2015. Starlink also opened a user terminal manufacturing facility near Bastrop, Texas in December 2023, which produced one million terminals in its first nine months and was on track to become the largest PCB factory in the US.",
    "SpaceX operates four orbital launch sites: Cape Canaveral Space Force Station (SLC-40) and Kennedy Space Center (LC-39A) in Florida for Falcon rockets, Vandenberg Space Force Base in California (SLC-4E) for polar orbit missions, and Starbase near Brownsville, Texas for Starship. Before retirement, all Falcon 1 launches took place at Omelek Island.",
    "Inspiration4 was the first all-civilian orbital spaceflight, launched in 2021 on behalf of Shift4 Payments CEO Jared Isaacman. The Crew Dragon Resilience launched from Kennedy Space Center LC-39A on a Falcon 9, orbited Earth for about three days, then splashed down in the Atlantic. All four crew members received commercial astronaut training from SpaceX.",
    "Gwynne Shotwell serves as President and COO of SpaceX. She maintains her primary office at the McGregor, Texas test facility. In November 2022, she was announced to oversee Starbase alongside VP Mark Juncosa, demonstrating the urgency to get Starship flying.",
    "SpaceX's board of directors includes Elon Musk (founder, chairman, CEO, CTO), Kimbal Musk (board member since 2002), Gwynne Shotwell (President and COO), Luke Nosek (co-founder of PayPal, joined 2009), Steve Jurvetson (co-founder of Future Ventures), Antonio Gracias (CEO of Valor Equity Partners, joined 2010), and Donald Harrison (President of global partnerships at Google, joined 2015).",
    "SpaceX's valuation has grown from approximately $2.4 billion in 2012 to $350 billion by December 2024. Key milestones include $10 billion in 2014, $21 billion in 2017, $74 billion in February 2021, $100 billion in October 2021, $127 billion in August 2022, $180 billion in December 2023, and approximately $400 billion by July 2025.",
    "SpaceX's revenue grew from $1.8 billion in 2020 to $2.3 billion in 2021, $4.6 billion in 2022, approximately $9 billion in 2023, $13.1 billion in 2024, and approximately $15.5 billion projected for 2025. Starlink subscription revenue has been a major growth driver.",
    "SpaceX had approximately 30 employees at founding in 2002. The company grew to about 600 by December 2008, over 1,000 by 2010, approximately 7,000 by 2017, over 9,500 by March 2021, approximately 12,000 by April 2022, and over 13,000 by September 2023.",
    "SpaceX has won numerous military contracts: an IDIQ contract allowing up to $100 million in Air Force launches in 2005, a $1 billion NASA IDIQ contract, Deep Space Climate Observatory and STP-2 DoD missions, GPS III satellite launches, and National Security Space Launch contracts. In August 2020, SpaceX won a $316 million NSSL contract for 40% of US military satellite launches over 5-7 years.",
    "SpaceX broke ULA's monopoly on US military classified payload launches when Falcon 9 v1.1 was certified for National Security Space Launch in 2015. ULA had held a monopoly since 2006. In April 2016, SpaceX won the first national security launch contract to launch GPS III for $82.7 million, approximately 40% less than previous comparable missions.",
    "SpaceX launched GPS III satellites for the US Air Force. The first contract was awarded in April 2016 for $82.7 million. In March 2018, SpaceX secured an additional $290 million contract to launch three more GPS III satellites. The third GPS III was launched on June 20, 2020.",
    "The National Reconnaissance Office (NRO) purchased its first SpaceX launch in May 2017. In February 2019, SpaceX secured a $297 million contract for three NRO missions. In March 2024, Reuters reported SpaceX is building a network of hundreds of spy satellites under a $1.8 billion NRO contract signed in 2021.",
    "NASA estimated it would have cost approximately $4 billion to develop a rocket like Falcon 9 using traditional contracting processes — about ten times SpaceX's actual development cost of $390 million (including Falcon 1). In May 2020, NASA administrator Jim Bridenstine noted that US investments in SpaceX helped the country capture 70% of the commercial launch market.",
    "Starlink opened a user terminal manufacturing facility near Bastrop, Texas in December 2023. In its first nine months, the one-million-square-foot facility produced one million user terminals and was on track to become the largest factory for printed circuit boards in the United States.",
    "SpaceX faced environmental challenges at Boca Chica including citations from the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality in August 2024 for violating regulations by releasing pollutants into water. The EPA fined SpaceX approximately $150,000 for discharging industrial wastewater and violating the Clean Water Act. Environmental groups challenged the FAA's environmental review process for Starship launches.",
    "The first Starship integrated flight test took place in April 2023. It was delayed due to regulatory approvals from the FAA. During the flight, the vehicle exploded. This test was significant as the first attempt to launch the combined Starship upper stage and Super Heavy booster together.",
    "Falcon 9 has a published price of $56.5 million per launch to low Earth orbit, making it the least expensive orbital launch vehicle in the industry. This pricing has pressured competitors; European satellite operators pushed ESA to reduce Ariane 5 and Ariane 6 prices, and ULA announced major restructuring to halve launch costs.",
    "Crew Dragon Demo-2 launched on May 30, 2020, carrying NASA astronauts Bob Behnken and Doug Hurley to the ISS. It was the first time a crewed vehicle had launched from the US since the Space Shuttle's retirement in 2011, and the first SpaceX commercial crewed launch. This mission ended US dependence on Russian Soyuz vehicles at approximately $80 million per seat.",
    "As of 2024, SpaceX operates Rideshare and Bandwagon (mid inclination) programs providing additional competition for small satellite launchers. These programs allow multiple small payloads to share a single Falcon 9 launch, significantly reducing per-payload costs.",
    "SpaceX has faced workplace culture issues including claims of workplace sexual harassment from five former employees published in December 2021, ranging from interns to engineers. In May 2022, Business Insider alleged Musk engaged in sexual misconduct with a SpaceX flight attendant in 2016. Employees wrote an open letter condemning Musk's behavior.",
    "Super Heavy is the first-stage booster of SpaceX's Starship launch system. Together with the Starship upper stage, it forms the fully reusable super heavy-lift system. Super Heavy uses Raptor engines burning liquid methane and liquid oxygen. It is designed to be caught and reused, similar to Falcon 9 booster recovery.",
    "Kennedy Space Center Launch Complex 39A was leased by SpaceX in April 2014 for 20 years. It was modified for Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy launches and is the only pad supporting Falcon Heavy. SpaceX launched its first crewed ISS mission from 39A on May 30, 2020. The pad has been prepared since 2019 to eventually accommodate Starship launches.",
    "SpaceX CRS-1 was the first of 12 planned Commercial Resupply Services missions, launched in October 2012. It achieved orbit, berthed with the ISS, remained on station for 20 days, then re-entered and splashed down in the Pacific Ocean. CRS missions have since flown approximately twice a year.",
    "According to NASA's independently verified numbers, SpaceX's total development cost for Falcon 9 (including Falcon 1) was approximately $390 million. NASA estimated it would have cost about $4 billion using traditional contracting — 4 to 10 times more. Congressional testimony in 2017 credited NASA's Space Act Agreement approach of setting high-level requirements while leaving details to industry.",
    "The Sabatier reaction synthesizes methane from atmospheric CO2 and water ice. SpaceX chose liquid methane as Starship's propellant specifically because methane can be produced on Mars using this reaction, enabling in-situ propellant production for return flights and making Mars colonization more feasible.",
    "SpaceX designs and launches custom military satellites for the Space Development Agency as part of a missile defense system in low Earth orbit. The constellation would give the US capabilities to sense, target, and potentially intercept nuclear missiles and hypersonic weapons. Both China and Russia have raised concerns at the United Nations about the program.",
    "The Falcon 9 v1.1 was certified for National Security Space Launch in 2015, making SpaceX eligible to compete for US Air Force classified payload launches. This broke the monopoly that United Launch Alliance had held since 2006, introducing competition and significantly reducing launch costs for government missions.",
    "SpaceX's low launch prices, especially for geostationary transfer orbit missions, have pressured European competitors. European satellite operators pushed ESA to reduce Ariane 5 and Ariane 6 prices. Prior to 2013, the commercial launch market was dominated by Arianespace (Ariane 5) and International Launch Services (Proton). ULA announced restructuring to cut costs by half due to SpaceX competition.",
    "Starbase is SpaceX's Starship development and launch facility near Brownsville, Texas (Boca Chica). It is one of SpaceX's four orbital launch sites and is dedicated to Starship launches. In November 2022, COO Gwynne Shotwell and VP Mark Juncosa were assigned to oversee the facility, reflecting urgency to get Starship flying.",
]

